WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.880
 Hello and welcome to another computer architecture CPU emulator walkthrough.

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:09.400
 And so in this one we are going to go through a number of simple samples.

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:13.800
 And I will turn on the viewing of the assembly language down here, so we can see that.

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:15.300
 This one here is really simple.

00:00:15.300 --> 00:00:20.440
 It is going to load a constant into the A register, 27, that's a decimal 27.

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:23.760
 And then we're going to add 15, so this is going to be 27 plus 15.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:28.120
 And then we're going to store it into memory location 00, and then we're going to stop.

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.360
 So this is going to cause a little bit of output.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:35.120
 So let's go ahead and narrate the execution, and then start it running.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:39.760
 I'll put this in a place where we don't want to hide the memory, because the action is

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:41.280
 going to happen here in the memory.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:42.280
 So here we go.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:54.320
 PC 0x00, load the accumulator immediate 0x1B, PC 0x02, add will carry immediate 0x0F, PC

00:00:54.320 --> 00:01:04.640
 0x04, store accumulator to address 0, PC 0x06, break printed output asterisk.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:09.880
 So this time we stored something in the memory, so the program will dump the memory up to

00:01:09.880 --> 00:01:11.880
 a 0 byte, kind of like C, right?

00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:18.120
 It will dump the memory up to a 0 byte, and 0x2A, let's go look at our ASCII chart.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:23.440
 0x2A, 0x2A, 0x2A, there we go.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:27.800
 Is a 42 decimal, interesting choice of number, and it's an asterisk.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:33.280
 And so it's a 0x2A, you can see it in the memory, and when the program stops, it prints

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:34.280
 it out.

00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:35.280
 Okay?

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:39.000
 So then let's take a look at another simple example.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.040
 Let's take a look at the assembly language for it.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:48.120
 So this is going to basically stick that letter H into the accumulator, then store it in memory

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:53.600
 location 0, and then put a high in the accumulator, and store that in memory location 1.

00:01:53.600 --> 00:02:01.080
 So let's go ahead and step that, PC 0x00, load accumulator immediately at 0x48.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:07.800
 I'll go to the next instruction, which is going to store that one.

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:12.640
 PC 0x02, store accumulator to address 0.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:17.440
 So we took what was in the accumulator and stored it into memory address 0, and now we're

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:19.600
 going to load the I.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:26.260
 PC 0x04, load accumulator immediately at 0x69.

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:29.560
 So 0x69 is the letter I, and now we're going to store it.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:34.480
 PC 0x06, store accumulator to address 1.

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:37.720
 We just put some data into memory location 1.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:41.080
 We're going to step one more, and it's going to stop, and it's going to print out what

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:43.080
 is here in ASCII.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:48.680
 PC 0x08, break, print, hit output, hi.

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:51.640
 So it said hi.

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:55.800
 And so let's do one more simple one, and this one's kind of weird.

00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:01.000
 So I have a single instruction, which is break, which is stop, and you'll notice it says zero

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.040
 zero zero right away, but I used an assembly language data pseudo-op, we call these pseudo-ops,

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:11.360
 and it preloads the data, and it says, and this is hello world, so you can see it's hello

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:15.400
 world in ASCII, 0x20 is the space.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:19.280
 So we're just going to run this, but it's going to immediately stop, but it's going

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:23.400
 to dump the memory because we preloaded data into memory, and so this is really showing

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:26.520
 you more about how this data pseudo-operation works.

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:32.720
 PC 0x00, break, print, hit output, hello world.

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:38.280
 Okay, and so let me then show you one more thing in this.

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:42.960
 You can write code in the assembler, okay?

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:44.780
 This is a little text editor.

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:48.180
 You read the assembly language, you go into the documentation, read the assembly language,

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:51.880
 and then you can say take this code and assemble it.

00:03:51.880 --> 00:04:00.340
 So it assembled it, and so now it says hello CA for E, so there's the, so in location five

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:03.040
 is the space, and then C is the 43.

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:09.040
 Let's go ahead and bring up a ASCII chart so we can figure out what this memory location

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:10.120
 six is.

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:17.200
 It's a 0x43, and that's C, and then 41 is the A, right?

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:19.400
 So you can kind of see this, and now we're going to run it.

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:23.120
 It's only got one instruction, which is a stop instruction, but then it's going to print

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:24.120
 out its.

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:30.320
 PC 0x00, break, print, hit output, hello CA for E.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:35.280
 That's just really showing you the data thing, and later we will use this to preload data

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:40.000
 and then write code that reads from memory and does something to that memory.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.560
 But for now I hope you found this walkthrough with a couple of simple examples useful.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:45.060
 Cheers.

